        "title": "fix(docker): precreate owned named volume targets",
        "body": "Summary:\n- pre-create Docker named-volume mount points for workspace and auth-profile config dirs\n- verify each mount point is node-owned with 0700 permissions before switching to the node user\n- update Dockerfile coverage for the additional paths\n\nVerification:\n- `pnpm test src/dockerfile.test.ts`\n- `.agents/skills/autoreview/scripts/autoreview --mode local`\n\nBehavior addressed:\nFirst-run Docker named volumes mounted at `/home/node/.openclaw/workspace` and `/home/node/.config/openclaw` could start as root-owned directories, blocking the non-root `node` runtime from writing workspace or auth-profile state.\n\nReal environment tested:\nLocal macOS checkout with Dockerfile unit coverage.\n\nExact steps or command run after this patch:\n`pnpm test src/dockerfile.test.ts`\n\nEvidence after fix:\nThe Dockerfile now creates `/home/node/.openclaw`, `/home/node/.openclaw/workspace`, and `/home/node/.config/openclaw` with `install -d -m 0700 -o node -g node`, and the test asserts those ownership checks happen before `USER node`.\n\nObserved result after fix:\n1 Vitest file passed, 18 tests passed; autoreview reported no accepted/actionable findings.\n\nWhat was not tested:\nA live Docker build/run with fresh named volumes; the patch is constrained to the image-layer mount-point ownership contract and covered by Dockerfile assertions.\n\nFixes #85076.\n",
